If you plan to place the hot tub in a location that was previously lawn, you have two ways to do this. The first is to take an 8 foot (2.4 meters) by 8 foot (2.4 meters) section of lawn out and dig down past the sod to undisturbed soil. Then fill the excavation with gravel and level. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a9/Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The second is to build a deck strong enough to support the weight of a hot tub filled with water and people enjoying themselves. You can use the plan below to construct a hot tub deck in one afternoon. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Build-a-Hot-Tub-Platform-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
